To start, notice that $24\cdot 50 = 1200\equiv 1\pmod{1199}$ (in other words, $24$ and $50$ are inverses modulo $1199$).

To solve the congruence $24x\equiv 15\pmod{1199}$, we multiply both sides by $50$ and simplify: \begin{align*}
50\cdot 24x &\equiv 50\cdot 15 \pmod{1199} \\
x &\equiv 750 \pmod{1199}
\end{align*}This process can also be reversed (by multiplying both sides by $50^{-1}=24$), so the solutions to the original congruence are precisely the same as the solutions to $x\equiv 750\pmod{1199}$. The largest negative solution is $750-1199 = \boxed{-449}$.

chat_and_reason.content:
First, we can simplify the given congruence by dividing both sides by the greatest common divisor of 24 and 1199, which is 1. So we have $$24x \equiv 15 \pmod{1199}.$$ 

Next, we can use the extended Euclidean algorithm to find the modular inverse of 24 modulo 1199. We want to find an integer $y$ such that $24y \equiv 1 \pmod{1199}$. Using the extended Euclidean algorithm, we have:

\begin{align*}
1199 &= 24 \cdot 49 + 23 \\
24 &= 23 \cdot 1 + 1
\end{align*}

Working backwards, we can express 1 as a linear combination of 24 and 1199:

\begin{align*}
1 &= 24 - 23 \cdot 1 \\
&= 24 - (1199 - 24 \cdot 49) \\
&= 50 \cdot 24 - 1199 \cdot 1
\end{align*}

Therefore, the modular inverse of 24 modulo 1199 is 50. Multiplying both sides of the congruence by 50, we get:

\begin{align*}
24x &\equiv 15 \pmod{1199} \\
\Rightarrow \quad 50 \cdot 24x &\equiv 50 \cdot 15 \pmod{1199} \\
\Rightarrow \quad x &\equiv 750 \pmod{1199}
\end{align*}

So the largest negative integer $x$ satisfying the given congruence is $x = 750 - 1199 = \boxed{-449}$.

